  "final_answer": "## FY2025 Connectivity Segment: EBITDA-to-Operating-Income Gap\n\n### The Numbers\n\nFrom the Segment Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation table in the SpaceX S-1:\n\n| Line Item | FY2025 ($ millions) |\n|---|---|\n| **Income (loss) from operations** | **$4,423** |\n| Add: Depreciation and amortization | 2,376 |\n| Add: Share-based compensation | 369 |\n| Add: Restructuring charges | — |\n| Add: Impairment | — |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$7,168** |\n\n### The Implied Gap\n\nThe EBITDA-to-operating-income gap is:\n\n**$7,168 million – $4,423 million = $2,745 million**\n\nThis $2,745 million gap is composed entirely of two adjustments:\n- **Depreciation and amortization: $2,376 million** (86.6% of the gap)\n- **Share-based compensation: $369 million** (13.4% of the gap)\n\nDepreciation and amortization is by far the dominant driver of the wedge between GAAP operating income and the non-GAAP Segment Adjusted EBITDA.\n\n---\n\n### Why Satellite Depreciation Is Economically Recurring Even Though Excluded from Adjusted EBITDA\n\nThe S-1 defines Segment Adjusted EBITDA as segment income (loss) from operations excluding depreciation and amortization, share-based compensation, restructuring charges, and impairment. Depreciation is excluded under the logic that it is a non-cash expense \"that management believes does not directly reflect ongoing operating performance.\"\n\nHowever, Starlink satellite depreciation is **economically recurring** for several reasons grounded in the filing's own disclosures:\n\n**1. Satellites have exceptionally short useful lives.**\n\nThe S-1 states that broadband satellites have a **five-year useful life** and first-generation mobile satellites have a **three-year useful life**. These are among the shortest-lived productive assets in any capital-intensive industry. Unlike a factory or building depreciated over 20–30 years, a Starlink satellite becomes obsolete — physically deorbits — within a single presidential term.\n\n**2. The constellation requires continuous, indefinite replenishment.**\n\nThe Risk Factors section explicitly warns:\n\n> \"the useful life of our satellites is inherently shorter than that of the information technology systems and infrastructure they host. As a result, we must periodically launch replacement satellites as existing satellites reach the end of their useful lives and are decommissioned, which may truncate the effective lifespan of those underlying information technology systems and infrastructure.\"\n\nThis is not a one-time buildout followed by a long harvest period. The Starlink business model structurally requires a perpetual cycle of manufacturing and launching replacement satellites. Depreciation is the GAAP mechanism that spreads the cost of those satellites over their brief service lives, and the capital outlays to replace them are recurring cash costs that will persist for as long as the Connectivity segment operates.\n\n**3. The capital costs being depreciated are real and recurring.**\n\nSatellite assets on the balance sheet include both manufacturing costs (parts, labor, overhead) and capitalized launch costs (including an allocation of flight-vehicle depreciation from the Space segment). Every satellite in orbit represents real cash that was spent to build and launch it. When that satellite reaches end-of-life, real cash must be spent again to build and launch its replacement. Depreciation matches that economic consumption to the periods benefiting from the asset.\n\n**4. The materiality is enormous and the sensitivity confirms the economic exposure.**\n\nThe S-1 discloses that a one-year change in the average useful life of satellite assets would have an approximately **$480 million impact on operating income** for FY2025. This sensitivity demonstrates that satellite depreciation is not a minor, discretionary accounting entry — it represents a core, ongoing economic cost of operating the Connectivity business that is highly sensitive to real-world engineering and operational variables (propellant life, on-orbit performance, utilization patterns).\n\n**5. The standard non-GAAP critique applies with unusual force here.**\n\nManagement's rationale for exclusion — that depreciation \"does not directly reflect ongoing operating performance\" — is the conventional justification used across industries. But for most companies, depreciating assets have multi-decade lives and the depreciation charge is a distant proxy for actual replacement spending. For Starlink, the 3-to-5-year asset life means depreciation tracks actual economic consumption far more closely. A dollar of satellite depreciation today corresponds to a dollar of replacement CapEx within a short and predictable horizon. Treating it as a non-recurring or non-operational item misrepresents the economic reality of a business that must continuously rebuild its own productive infrastructure.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nThe $2,745 million EBITDA-to-operating-income gap is predominantly attributable to satellite and launch-vehicle depreciation ($2,376 million). While Adjusted EBITDA excludes depreciation as a non-cash item under standard non-GAAP convention, Starlink's 3–5 year satellite lifespans and the perpetual constellation-replenishment requirement mean that depreciation here is a close proxy for an unavoidable, economically recurring cash cost — not a distant accounting artifact. Investors relying on Segment Adjusted EBITDA as a proxy for \"run-rate\" earnings power should recognize that a material portion of the excluded depreciation represents near-term, non-discretionary capital replacement spending.",
